  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM refers to the anxiety and stress that individuals from underrepresented groups experience when they are aware that their group is stereotyped as less capable in science, technology, engineering, and mathematics fields. As a retired educator and former high school teacher in Chicago, I've witnessed firsthand how this phenomenon can hinder academic performance and discourage students from pursuing STEM careers. Growing up in a household where my father was a PhD holder and my mother had an upper secondary education, I was fortunate to have a strong foundation, but I also saw how stereotypes could still affect my students. For instance, a young girl once told me she felt her math skills were 'not good enough' because she was the only girl in her class, which led her to avoid advanced math courses. This is a clear example of stereotype threat at work. I believe we absolutely must address stereotype threat in STEM. The solution lies in creating inclusive learning environments where students feel safe to express themselves without fear of judgment. Schools should implement mentorship programs that pair students with role models from diverse backgrounds, and teachers should be trained to recognize and counteract stereotypes. Additionally, promoting positive media representations of women and minorities in STEM fields can help shift cultural narratives. As someone who spends several hours daily on social media, I’ve seen how online communities can be powerful tools for fostering support and collaboration among students. By combining these strategies, we can help ensure that every student has the opportunity to thrive in STEM, regardless of their background. It’s not just about fixing individual cases; it’s about building a culture that values diversity and equity from the ground up.",
